HTML:
SushiOS Syntax

Files

Apps should be structured as follows:

 /SushiOS/Apps/Example.bento/ /SushiOS/Apps/Example.bento/.ssys/ /SushiOS/Apps/Example.bento/.html/

HTML and SSYS files should always run within a .bento file. To run the .bento file, simply run the file.run command and enter the bento file (e.g., /SushiOS/Apps/Example.bento/).

You can also run .ssys and .html files directly by using the file.run command and entering the file path.

Documents should follow this structure:

 /SushiOS/Documents/Example.txt/

Documents (e.g., .txt files) are stored separately in the Documents folder and can be accessed or edited as needed.

SYSS Code

SYSS code is a way to run commands in Core through code. Commands and their inputs are separated by a ^ symbol.

 file.run^/SushiOS/Apps/Example.bento/.html/^This is an example!

Important: You can only run one command of SYSS in your SYSS code due to security reasons.

Note: SYSS code is used to automate tasks within the SushiOS environment, such as running applications or loading documents.

Command Definitions

help

Gives you all the commands.

file.run

Runs a file.

file.list

Lists your files.

file.delete

Deletes a file.

file.create

Creates a file.

file.edit

Edits a file.

file.read

Shows the raw form of a file.

save.system

Saves the system as a file.

save.system.to.ip

Saves the system to your IP.

maki.store

Opens the app store and allows you to download an app.

maki.create

Allows you to create an app for the Maki Store (app store).

sushiguard.scan

Runs SushiOS’s built-in antivirus scanner.
